, which forms a distinct hierarchy of categories for nation-state status. However, unlike these categories, Fourth World denotes <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../754/21754.xml">
nations</link> without <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../151/28151.xml">
states</link>. This sense emphasizes the non-recognition or exclusion of often ethnically or religiously defined groups from the political and economic world system. Examples of Fourth World nations include the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../152/26152.xml">
Roma</link> worldwide, pre-<conflict wordnetid="100958896" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../461/4764461.xml">
WWI</link></conflict>
 <ethnic_group wordnetid="107967382" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../184/150184.xml">
Ashkenazi</link></ethnic_group>
 in the region of the <politics wordnetid="113840719" confidence="0.8">
<social_group wordnetid="107950920" confidence="0.8">
<social_relation wordnetid="100032823" confidence="0.8">
<gathering wordnetid="107975026" confidence="0.8">
